M|rules|title: Cross-Request LRU Caching
M|rules|impact: HIGH
M|rules|impactDescription: caches across requests
M|rules|tags: server, cache, lru, cross-request
M|rules|`React.cache()` only works within one request. For data shared across sequential requests (user clicks button A then button B), use an LRU cache.
M|rules|**Implementation:**
M|rules|```typescript
M|rules|import { LRUCache } from 'lru-cache'
M|rules|const cache = new LRUCache<string, any>({
M|rules|max: 1000,
M|rules|ttl: 5 * 60 * 1000  // 5 minutes
M|rules|})
M|rules|export async function getUser(id: string) {
M|rules|const cached = cache.get(id)
M|rules|if (cached) return cached
M|rules|const user = await db.user.findUnique({ where: { id } })
M|rules|cache.set(id, user)
M|rules|return user
M|rules|}
M|rules|// Request 1: DB query, result cached
M|rules|// Request 2: cache hit, no DB query
M|rules|```
M|rules|Use when sequential user actions hit multiple endpoints needing the same data within seconds.
M|rules|**With Vercel's [Fluid Compute](https://vercel.com/docs/fluid-compute):** LRU caching is especially effective because multiple concurrent requests can share the same function instance and cache. This 
M|rules|**In traditional serverless:** Each invocation runs in isolation, so consider Redis for cross-process caching.
M|rules|Reference: [https://github.com/isaacs/node-lru-cache](https://github.com/isaacs/node-lru-cache)